Patch Set 5:

With this, the newer sources added in
https://github.com/google/oss-fuzz/compare/master...rlohning:use_dependencies?expand=1
will be used.
Uploaded patch set 6.
Patch Set 6: Sanity-Review+1

Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

FWIW, here’s what I do locally:

* clone qt5.git via init-repository
* check out dev for all submodules or use the synchronize script (I use worktrees, but not relevant for your docker image)
* rename qt5.git’s .git directory so that git no longer cares about it

That way I have the toplevel build system (so don’t have to build the submodules in the right order) without any of the submodule stuff I don’t need (and that makes a lot of noise in VS Code).

But well, it’s not like the submodule build order changes a lot, so having a shellscript build things in order will do just fine I suppose. Until it doesn’t 🤪

Patch Set 6:

> Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2
> 
> But well, it’s not like the submodule build order changes a lot, so having a shellscript build things in order will do just fine I suppose. Until it doesn’t 🤪

oss-fuzz is only building qtbase and qtsvg, so this problem is trivial. I dare relying on always having to build qtbase first. ;-)
Should further modules get involved, matching all their dependencies at the same time might become tricky already. That probably won't happen in the foreseeable future, though.

Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

While the patch in itself should be fine, it still has to wait until https://github.com/google/oss-fuzz/pull/7017 was merged into oss-fuzz.

Patch Set 6: -Code-Review

> Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1
> 
> While the patch in itself should be fine, it still has to wait until https://github.com/google/oss-fuzz/pull/7017 was merged into oss-fuzz.

Here we go...

Patch Set 2:

The animation pause on tooltip hover issue with my example, and my actual app, is definitely fixed, so +1 for that, and thank you.

In my actual app with some "real" animations going on I'm now getting a bit of stuttering when the window is being resized. It's not horrible by any means, and in practical terms not a big deal. I'm mentioning it in case it might be indicative of some bigger issue. With 5.12 it's much smoother, and also with 5.14.1 (Win7/MSVC '17). I'm having a hard time coming up with a repro scenario where it's obvious. Also those other Qt versions are pre-built, and this one I'm obviously building myself, so that's another potential difference (don't know what exactly, but maybe). So, big grain of salt there, for sure, and this new version is certainly an improvement where it matters.

I'm not sure how else to test this besides the animation thing (what else this may affect). I see someone else filed something about a menu being slow to open, but no repro case there either.

messages.message: Uploaded patch set 1.
Patch Set 1: Sanity-Review+1

Patch Set 1:

Looks good in general, I tested lowenergyscanner in the three cases:
1) with powered on BT adapter (works as expected)
2) without BT adapter (I get the intended warning)
3) turning the BT adapter off (I get the intended warning)

On #2 the lowenergyscanner does not recover when I plug in the adapter. It does not give an error and says it is scanning, but it will not find anything (tried three times). Not sure if this is due to Windows bluetooth, the example app, or something else? Restarting the application helps and devices are found again. This is not a big deal but would be interesting to understand as:

The #3 will recover. When I turn on the plugged adapter, it will scan and find devices without the need to restart the application.

Patch Set 1:

> Patch Set 1:
> 
> Looks good in general, I tested lowenergyscanner in the three cases:
> 1) with powered on BT adapter (works as expected)
> 2) without BT adapter (I get the intended warning)
> 3) turning the BT adapter off (I get the intended warning)
> 
> On #2 the lowenergyscanner does not recover when I plug in the adapter. It does not give an error and says it is scanning, but it will not find anything (tried three times). Not sure if this is due to Windows bluetooth, the example app, or something else? Restarting the application helps and devices are found again. This is not a big deal but would be interesting to understand as:
> 
> The #3 will recover. When I turn on the plugged adapter, it will scan and find devices without the need to restart the application.

#2 seems to be the intentional behavior. From the QBluetoothDeviceDiscoveryAgent::start():

 if (!isActive() && d->lastError != InvalidBluetoothAdapterError)
        d->start(methods);

In the #2 case I return the InvalidBluetoothAdapterError.
I can change it to general QBluetoothDeviceDiscoveryAgent::InputOutputError, like BlueZ and Android do. However, the error description makes me think that InvalidBluetoothAdapterError is the right choice here...

The other option would be to fix the condition in QBluetoothDeviceDiscoveryAgent::start, but I'm not sure that it would not break behavior on other platforms.

Patch Set 1:

> > 1) with powered on BT adapter (works as expected)

> > 3) turning the BT adapter off (I get the intended warning)
> > 
> > On #2 the lowenergyscanner does not recover when I plug in the adapter. It does not give an error and says it is scanning, but it will not find anything (tried three times). Not sure if this is due to Windows bluetooth, the example app, or something else? Restarting the application helps and devices are found again. This is not a big deal but would be interesting to understand as:
> > 
> > The #3 will recover. When I turn on the plugged adapter, it will scan and find devices without the need to restart the application.
> 
> #2 seems to be the intentional behavior. From the QBluetoothDeviceDiscoveryAgent::start():
> 
>  if (!isActive() && d->lastError != InvalidBluetoothAdapterError)
>         d->start(methods);
> 
> In the #2 case I return the InvalidBluetoothAdapterError.
> I can change it to general QBluetoothDeviceDiscoveryAgent::InputOutputError, like BlueZ and Android do. However, the error description makes me think that InvalidBluetoothAdapterError is the right choice here...
> 
> The other option would be to fix the condition in QBluetoothDeviceDiscoveryAgent::start, but I'm not sure that it would not break behavior on other platforms.

Admittedly this is a corner case and I think not really a "problem" of this patch.

Here's my understanding of our platforms behaviour, which seem inconsistent:

- Bluez::start() checks the adapter existence every time. It uses different error code so it will retry every time
- Win::start() checks the adapter existence every time, thanks to this patch
- Android::start() checks the adapter existence every time.  It uses different error code so it will retry every time
- macOS::start() has its own check for the adapter not found in the constructor. We'd need to move the adapter check from discovery agent constructor to start() if we'd want to harmonize the behavior.

==> with current patch-set and codebase Bluez and Android will retry every time, while Windows and macOS will bail out after first adapter-not-found fail.

We could harmonize the behaviours of Bluez, Win, and Android by removing the error check from the baseclass start() methods (there are 2 of them). In addition we need to remove the assert from macOS:
https://code.qt.io/cgit/qt/qtconnectivity.git/tree/src/bluetooth/qbluetoothdevicediscoveryagent_darwin.mm#n151

This would also "fix" the lowenergyscanner. If there is no BT adapter it will show "InvalidAdapterError" on the first click on "Scan button", but if you click it again, it will say it is scanning for devices. It really isn't scanning, but this happens because it doesn't get the error signal which triggers the text change on the UI.

Patch Set 1:

Hi. Please review.
Also please note that there is one more problem - I actually had to re-zip the original archive, because it was not correctly processed by QZipReader. The original archive, when read, didn't report separate entries for directories, only for files, so QZipReader failed to create proper directory hierarchy. This looks like a bug of the software that was used to create the original zip archive (or probably is was just some earlier version of zip format?).
After re-zipping it, the problem was fixed. The content of the archive didn't change, of course.

If we really want to keep *the original* zip archive, we also need to patch QZipReader. However, I checked how the zip archives are created on up-to-date Ubuntu, Windows, and macOS, and I do not see the problems, that I faced with the original zip archive.

The original archive, when read, didn't report separate entries for directories, only for files, so QZipReader failed to create proper directory hierarchy. This looks like a bug of the software that was used to create the original zip archive (or probably is was just some earlier version of zip format?).
> > After re-zipping it, the problem was fixed. The content of the archive didn't change, of course.
> > 
> > If we really want to keep *the original* zip archive, we also need to patch QZipReader. However, I checked how the zip archives are created on up-to-date Ubuntu, Windows, and macOS, and I do not see the problems, that I faced with the original zip archive.
> 
> Ideally, we should use the original zip archive. Have you checked how hard it would be to support that in qzipreader?

https://codereview.qt-project.org/c/qt/qtbase/+/387106/1 contains the patch to QZipReader.
I also updated this patch to use the original archive now.

messages.message: Uploaded patch set 1.
Patch Set 1: Sanity-Review+1

Patch Set 1:

Not sure if switching from FixedRunConfigurationFactory to RunConfigurationFactory has other undesired side effects (does anyone know?). But we want one RunConfiguration per CMake target, and the Fixed* one only spits a single RunConfiguration for all targets. See ticket 26656 for an example ("thermo" demo on stm32 boards)

Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

You probably need to implement 

virtual QList<RunConfigurationCreationInfo> availableCreators(Target *target) const;


for your factory in order to see actual targets

Patch Set 1:

>

> virtual QList<RunConfigurationCreationInfo> availableCreators(Target *target) const;
